doc.title: Nexchip (688249.SS): Migrations to 4nm/28nm with stable capacity expansions; 2Q Rev/ NI in-line with the M missed; Buy
doc.source_uri: 2025-08-31/Nexchip 688249.SS Migrations to 40nm28nm with stable capacity expansions 2Q Rev NI in-line while GM missed BuyNexchip 68_2025-08-31

passages.text: 2Q Revenues (Rmb2.6bn, \(+21\%\) YoY/ \(^{100}\) QoQ) and Net income (Rmb197m, \(+83\%\) YoY/ \(+45\%\) QoQ) were in- line with pre- announcement, with GM of \(24\%\) lower QoQ due to increased D&A. Looking forward, we expect Nexchip to continuously ramp up productions with its new capacities, and see increasing contributions from more diverse products including CIS and PMIC. We remain positive on company's mix upgrade towards 55nm/40nm/28nm, and partnership with clients on featured products (e.g. cooperation with SmartSens on Stacked platform) to secure orders.
Read more: CHIPS Act 3: China Semis capex and Lithography.

2Q25 Rev/ Ni in- line with pre- announcement, while GM missed due to increased D&A. Nexchip's 2Q25 revenues came in at Rmb2.6bn (+21% YoY/ \(+2\%\) QoQ), in- line with GSe and the company's pre- announcement (Report link). GM down QoQ to \(24.3\%\) , which management attribute to increased D&A expenses as more capacities come online. Product mix has been improved, with DDIC revenues came down to \(61\%\) in 1H25, with CIS and PMIC revenues saw increasing contributions. With opex and non- op better than expected, Net income came in at Rmb197m (+83% YoY/ \(+45\%\) QoQ), in- line with the company's pre- announcement and \(18\%\) ahead of GSe.

Exhibit 1: Nexchip 2Q25 earnings snapshot
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Positive outlook on UT rates. The company's Aluminum process (mainly LCD driver/PMIC) is in full loading, while the Copper process (mainly CIS and high end LCD driver) now has a UT rate of \(70\%\) as it continuously expanding capacity for copper process. With the solid demand from customers, management is confident to ramp up to full loading by year end.

Capacity expansions continue. Management expect to add another \(20k\) wpm (wafer per month) capacities in 2H25, increasing total capacity to \(160k\) wpm. In 2026- 27, the company will stably add \(- 30k\) per year. Nexchip's \(40nm\) capacities have started generating revenues, and its \(28nm\) capacities will start mass production in end 2025 to early 2026.

ASP maintain stable. Management notes that competitions in the market remains, as major end markets have not seen significant recoveries. While UT rates have been strong, management does not seek to raise prices proactively. By segments, management expect strong orders from CIS thanks to the partnership with its strategic customers.

Earnings revision: We factor in Nexchip 2Q25 earnings and revise down earnings by \(4\% /6\% /5\%\) in 2025- 27E mainly on lower revenues of DDIC products, while we still expect revenue growth at \(19\% /32\% /16\%\) in 2025/26/27E on capacity increase and expansion to CIS products. We cut GM by 2.7ppts/0.2ppts/0.1ppts in 2025- 27E to reflect increasing D&A expenses due to capacity expansions, and revise down Opex by \(12\% /2\%\) in 2025/26E on better than expected expenses control (while we keep 2027E Opex largely unchanged).
Exhibit 2: Earnings revision
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Valuation: We are Buy-rated on Nexchip and update our 12-month target price to Rmb28.6 (vs. previously Rmb28.7) based on 43x 2026E target P/E (vs. 40x previously). Our target P/E multiple of 43x is based on the foundry peers' PEG & M at 0.7x (Exhibit 4), with peers including SMIC, a Hong, UMC and Vanguard, and the company's avg. earnings growth YoY in 2026- 27E at 48% YoY. Our target multiple at 43x is in line with the company's recent trading range at 40- 50x.
Exhibit 3:Nexchip P&L summary
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Valuation: We use near- term P/E to derive our target price for Nexchip, consistent with our China Semiconductor coverage. We base our 12- m TP of Rmb28.6 on a target P/E multiple of 43x forward year EPS (2026E). Our target P/E of 43x is derived from the foundry peers' PEG & M at 0.6x. We are Buy rated on Nexchip. Key Risks: Slower- than- expected capacity expansion; Weaker- than- expected demand in DDIC and CIS; Slower- than- expected R&D; intense competition.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
